@* DECISION 165's BOUNDARY. Now that a callback-less <EditForm> registers its submit, the obvious next
   question is why OnSubmit is not simply the callback for it. Because it is not the same callback:
   Blazor's OnSubmit means "handle every submit MYSELF, validation included", so an author who writes
   it is asking for the validation subsystem -- EditContext, field state, message stores -- which
   decision 138 refuses as a whole rather than pretending to have.

   The refusal is located and names the supported parameter. Suppressing the navigation was never the
   thing OnSubmit was for, and now that suppression happens with no callback at all, admitting OnSubmit
   as an alias for OnValidSubmit would be silently answering a different question than the one asked. *@

<EditForm Model="@model" OnSubmit="Save"><button id="s" type="submit">s</button></EditForm>

@code {
    private Person model = new Person();

    void Save() { }

    public record Person { public string Name { get; set; } = ""; }
}
